<br>
Cendan: &quot;First off you say I don't offer proof. Most people who claim to follow the Bible consider the Bible acceptable proof when discussing salvation, or any other issue.&quot;<br>
<br>
I am asking that you give a *reason* (apologia) for the hope of Christ you claim resides inside you. Merely telling me I am wrong is not offering reason. Providing an apologia for your faith is to offer reasonable evidence to support your view; whether the evidence is analysis of Biblical passages (exegesis), or extra-Biblical evidence such as archaelogical evidence. Make sense? Oh, Paul the Apostle commands to do as such when asked. Just an FYI.  <br>
<br>
Cendan:&quot;Actually when I looked it up the greek word is translated &quot;figure&quot;, as does the KJV, but I don't like the KJV so that isn't really important. NASB says &quot;corresponding.&quot; I don't encourage people to skip between versions to find one to fit their theology so I am going to continue using NASB, which I hear is regarded as the most accurate.&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
Actually, a thorough analysis of scripture can be accomplished by comparing various texts. I don't subscribe to the idea that there is an &quot;annointed version&quot; of the Bible as some do, being an atheist. Personally, I can deal with what ever text you want. I may refer to other texts only to help clarify a point I am making. <br>
<br>
<br>
Paul said, &quot;... we have redemption through his blood, the forgiveness of sins...&quot; (Eph 1:7). So let me ask you Cendan. Is it the blood of Christ that saves us or is it baptism?<br>
<br>
<br>
I want to start by dealing with Acts 2:38. &quot;Repent&quot; (2nd person plural) and &quot;be baptized&quot; (3rd person singular) and &quot;you will recieve the gift of the Holy Spirit&quot; (2nd person plural). Repent is a universal command to all people (Acts 17:30). &quot;Be baptized&quot; is specific to believers only (Acts 8:12).<br>
<br>
Acts 2:38 is saying &quot;repent&quot;, and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit, and each one of you (those who have already recieved the gift) be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ for the remission of sins. You should note the greek word for remission (aphesis) simply means &quot;release&quot;. Compare with Ephesians 1:7 where it is stated that it is through the blood of Christ that we obtain the aphesis (forgiveness) of sins! Cendan, do you need to go and find the literal blood of Christ and bathe in it in order to be forgiven? Of course not. It is clear that we are dealing with symbolic language. A good exegete will always consider passages with all that has been stated in the Bible concerning the topic at hand. That is why I pointed you to look at what Paul said about baptism. &quot;Baptism&quot; has always been a rite of passage in the Church. Those who are baptised are taking the mark of Christ and publicly declaring what happened to their hearts earlier. You know Paul said &quot;I thank God I baptised none of you....&quot; If he thought baptism was essential to salvation as you do, do you think he would have been thankful not to have baptised? Acts 2:38 means to be baptized for (because of) the forgiveness of sins. We aren’t baptized &quot;to get&quot; forgiveness of sin. Rather, because our sins have been forgiven, we should be baptized.<br>
<br>
Cendan: &quot;Actually when I looked it up the greek word is translated &quot;figure&quot;, as does the KJV, but I don't like the KJV so that isn't really important. NASB says &quot;corresponding.&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
Cendan, &quot;figure&quot; is also another meaning for the greek word antitupos and supports what I have said. It simply means a thing formed after some pattern. Compare with Hebrews 9:24 which uses antitupos regarding the &quot;Figure of the true&quot;.<br>
<br>
<br>
Cendan: &quot;Here is what you are saying it may say if you substitiure the NIV word. <br>
<br>
&quot;And symbolizing that, baptism now saves you—not the removal of dirt from the flesh, but an appeal to God for a good conscience — through the resurrection of Jesus Christ.&quot;<br>
<br>
Am I correct? I looked in the KJV, NIV, NAS, NASB, and the Greek and all say &quot;baptism now saves you.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
No Cendan it is not correct. Your are commiting a fallacy. You are isolating a particular phrase and then interpreting. The fallacy is called isogesis. Here read, Acts 10:47-48 &quot;Surely no one can refuse the water for these to be baptized who have received the Holy Spirit just as we did, can he?&quot; And he ordered them to be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ.&quot; What does that passage mean Cendan? If one has already recieved the Holy Spirit they are a child of God! Again, you must take into context what the Apostles taught, what Jesus taught. You can't just isolate phrases and then draw out doctrine.<br>
<br>
<br>
Cendan: &quot;So, would you then reason that Noah would have been saved even if he disobeyed God and didn't build an ark? No. You are right that the Ark didn't save Noah, but you are jumping to the wrong conclusion from there.&quot;<br>
<br>
No I am not jumping to the wrong conclusion. God was able to ask Noah to build the Ark why? Come on Cendan, you forget the Old Testament stories too easily.  God asked Noah because he was already a man righteous before God. Go back and re-read Genesis. It is clear. God knew that Noah would not refuse because Noah was already a God fearing believer.<br>
<br>
<br>
Cendan: &quot;Okay, I am looking at Romans 5:1 now. I don’t know what version you are looking at but I don’t see “alone” anywhere. I see in the NASB it says: “Therefore having been justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ,” which says that we have been justified and have peace with God through faith. Now, you may take that as saying that faith alone justifies us, but if you do then you need to explain vs 8 and 9 of the same chapter that say “But God demonstrates His own love toward us, in that while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us. Much more then, having now been justified by His blood, we shall be saved from the wrath of God through Him.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cendan, once again you are commiting a fallacy in Biblical exegesis. Here read John 3:16 &quot;For God so loved the world, that He gave His only begotten Son, that whoever believes in Him shall not perish, but have eternal life.&quot; John doesn't share your sentiment. Neither does the writer of Acts 10:43 &quot;Of Him all the prophets bear witness that through His name everyone who believes in Him receives forgiveness of sins.&quot; Again, it is clear that one is saved by faith in the grace of God alone.<br>
<br>
<br>
Cendan:&quot;First I don’t see anywhere that is “says” circumcision of the heart. In fact it is referring to the sinful ways of the life before baptism. Now, you were quick to point out the “corresponding to” in 1 Peter, are you now going to ignore that vs 12 is continuing from vs 11.? Note in particular the word “having.” Having been buried with Him in baptism they have been circumcised from the flesh. In which they were ALSO raised up with Him THROUGH faith in the working of God. I don’t know how to make that more clear, and anything I say would be redundant so I will wait to see how you respond to that. <br>
Paul is NOT comparing baptism with circumcision. He used the word to indicate the cutting away of the old life, and YES, he did use that term because they were familiar with it. Do I have to point out again that he is talking to the church of Colossae and he assumes the fact that they are baptized?&quot;<br>
<br>
Cendan, you made my point. Here, let me cut and paste for you: &quot;Having been buried with Him in baptism they have been circumcised from the flesh. In which they were ALSO raised up with Him THROUGH faith in the working of God.&quot; Now again, do you think Paul understood that the act of circumcision made one a Jew or do you think he firmly believed that those who are Jews already get circumcised as a symbol of their belief? BTW, note your emphasis on &quot;thorugh&quot; and compare with what I am saying above. Again, pretty clear that Baptism doesn't save. Only the saved get baptised.<br>
<br>
Now, you may wonder why I, an atheist, am interested in such topics. I have many friends who are Christians. I also have many family members who are devout fundamentalists who say no one is saved unless they follow a specific baptismal fomula. My interest is purely intellectual. Stimulating debate is good.<br>
<br>
Finally, even though I am an atheist I also feel a sense of community with all those interested in the pursuit of knowledge. Most of my Christian friends are truly interested in finding truth, or the pursuit of truth. It is a journey I enjoy walking with them. I also have Buddhist and Taoist friends all seeking the same: knowledge.<br>
<br>
